sidebar.title:
The Legacy of Arab Immigration Arab immigrants in the United States contribute to the nation’s rich culture with an estimated population of around three million persons. Arab immigrants trace their ancestry to various countries across the Arab world, including Lebanon, Syria, Egypt, Morocco, Iraq, Jordan, Palestine, Yemen, Tunisia, Algeria, and numerous Gulf countries. Their immigration history is marked by waves with the first wave of immigrants arriving between 1887 and 1913, driven by a quest for economic opportunities and the desire to secure financial stability potentially enabling them to invest in their ancestral villages or establish businesses upon their return. These first-wave Arab Americans engaged in unskilled labor with a majority being male and a large proportion being undereducated coming from mountainous or rural regions. Currently, Lebanon accounts for 32% of Arab American immigrants while 11% originate from Egypt (Arab American Institute Demographics 
   2024
). The second wave of immigrants came to the United States after World War II with an increase after the Palestinian-Israeli conflict and the enactment of the Immigration Act of 1965. Unlike the economically driven Lebanese Syrian Christians of the first wave, the majority of second-wave immigrants were refugees fleeing war-torn and politically unstable nations primarily occupied Palestine, Jordan, Iraq, Yemen, Lebanon, and Syria. From 2008 to 2018, immigrants from the Arab world originated from countries including Iraq, Egypt, Somalia, Morocco, and Lebanon with a large portion including professionals and individuals pursuing higher education who have chosen to remain in the United States (Arab American Institute Demographics 
   2024
). These migration patterns highlight the diverse socioeconomic factors influencing Arab immigration to the United States, ranging from economic aspirations to escaping conflict and seeking educational opportunities. Geographically, Arab immigrants reside in metropolitan areas with approximately 94% residing in urban centers. Large Arab American populations can be found in states such as Michigan, California, New York, Illinois, and Florida with cities like Dearborn (Michigan) and Los Angeles (California) hosting substantial Arab American communities (Arab American Institute Demographics 
   2024
).

Educational and Occupational Success Among Arab Americans People of Arab heritage, in general, prioritize professional occupations, emphasizing the importance of education as a pathway to white-collar careers. Recent data indicates that both US-born and foreign-born Arab Americans exhibit higher educational attainment compared to the national average. Over 90% of Arab Americans have completed high school, a contrast to 32% of the total U. S. population. Around 20% of Arab Americans hold post-graduate degrees. In comparison to European Americans, Arab Americans are more likely to be self-employed and hold managerial and professional specialty occupations. Around 45% are employed in managerial or professional roles while 29% work in sales and 16% in service positions. Arab American households in the United States have a mean annual income of $60,398, surpassing the national average of $52,029 for all households (Arab American Institute Demographics 
                  2024
               ). These data show the strong emphasis on education and professional success within the Arab American community contributing to their overall economic prosperity and higher-than-average household income.

Dominant Language and Dialects Arabic is the official language across the Arab world, including both modern and classical forms. Modern Standard Arabic is used in formal contexts such as written communication, radio broadcasts, and academic lectures while colloquial Arabic specific to each community is utilized for everyday spoken interactions (Suleiman 
                     2019
                  ). Arab individuals often blend Modern Standard Arabic and colloquial Arabic depending on the context and level of formality. The diversity of dialects, characterized by variations in accent, intonation, and vocabulary, can pose challenges in communication between Arab immigrants from different regions such as Syria and Lebanon compared to those from Iraq and Yemen (Suleiman 
                     2019
                  ). Generally, Arab communication is characterized by repetition and expressive gestures, especially in serious discussions which may be perceived as confrontational or aggressive by external observers. While English serves as a common second language in countries like Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon, Yemen, Iraq, and Kuwait, French is prevalent in Lebanon, Algeria, and Morocco. Literacy rates in the Arab world exhibit significant disparities ranging from 93% for men and 30% for women in Yemen to 95% for men and 85% for women in Jordan.

sidebar.para:
In personal relationships, verbal agreements hold greater significance than written contracts as they are seen as a matter of honor. Yet, in business dealings, there is an increasing reliance on written contracts. Arab culture places great emphasis on maintaining harmonious relationships and upholding dignity and honor. When faced with adversity or wrongdoing, Arabs often respond with a sense of resignation expressed through the phrase “ maalesh,” meaning “never mind; it doesn’t matter.” In challenging situations, individuals may be shielded from unpleasant news for as long as possible and informed gently when necessary. Disagreements are often hinted at indirectly or mediated through intermediaries to preserve social harmony and save face for all parties involved. This mediation process assures the petitioner that their concerns have been addressed with maximum influence and tact (Khosh et al. 
                     2020
                  ).

sidebar.title:
Predestination and Time Perception Among Arab Immigrants First-generation Arab immigrants often adhere to the belief in predestination that asserts that God has predetermined the events of one’s life. This belief encourages individuals to strive for the best outcomes while recognizing that ultimate control rests with a higher power. Plans and aspirations are often accompanied by the phrase “ inshallah,” meaning “if God wills,” signifying an acknowledgment of divine authority over one’s fate. Additionally, both blessings and misfortunes are commonly attributed to the will of God rather than solely to individual actions (Mpofu 
                     2018
                  ).

sidebar.para:
Titles hold significance in Arab culture and are typically used in conjunction with the individual’s first name. For instance, it is common to address someone as “Mr. Khalil” or “Dr. Ali.” Alternatively, some individuals may prefer to be addressed with familial titles, such as “mother” ( Um) or “father” ( Abu), followed by the name of their eldest son (e.g., Abu Khalil, which translates to “father of Khalil”). It is also customary for married women to retain their maiden names reflecting the importance of lineage and familial connections in Arab society (Suleiman 
                     2019
                  ).

In traditional Arab families, women are seen as subordinate to men. While husbands may hold obvious influence in public, wives often exercise significant power behind the scenes, particularly concerning domestic affairs and childcare. This power dynamic emphasizes the importance of understanding cultural intricacies within Arab families. Within extended families, decision-making authority often falls to older male figures, although women may gain influence with age, particularly after their children reach adulthood. The bond between mothers and sons is typically strong with sons often prioritizing their mother’s wishes and preferences. However, as nuclear families replace extended ones, these traditional norms are evolving (Aldossari and Chaudhry 
                     2024
                  ).

sidebar.title:
Parental Roles and Child Rearing in Traditional Arab FamiliesIn traditional Arab families, the roles of fathers and mothers concerning their children are clearly defined and distinct. Typically, fathers take on the role of disciplinarians while mothers serve as allies and mediators providing unwavering love and kindness. Although some fathers may believe in maintaining a degree of fear, family relationships are generally characterized by affection and sentimentality. Children are deeply cherished, indulged, and actively involved in all family activities (Abdul-Haq 
                     2018
                  ). Within Arab culture, the upbringing of children to reflect positively on the family is a significant responsibility. The character and achievements (or shortcomings) of a child are often attributed to the influence of upbringing and parental guidance. Given the emphasis on collective familism over individualism in Arab culture, adherence to adult rules is highly valued, and child-rearing practices are geared toward fostering accommodation and cooperation (Abdul-Haq 
                     2018
                  ).

sidebar.para:
Behaviors that may tarnish family honor, such as academic underachievement, sexual activity, substance use, and delinquency are actively avoided, especially among girls who are expected to uphold chastity and decency (Abdul-Haq 
                     2018
                  ). Adolescence in North America may offer Arab adolescents’ greater opportunities for academic achievement and more freedom in career choices compared to their counterparts in Arab countries. However, this career choice freedom can lead to cultural conflicts between American and Arab values causing significant tensions within Arab American families. Parents often express concerns about conflicting values regarding dating, extracurricular activities, alcohol consumption, and substance use among their children, highlighting the importance of understanding these cultural nuances for healthcare professionals.

sidebar.title:
Family Dynamics and Social StructuresIn Arab society, the family serves as the fundamental socioeconomic unit where members collaborate to ensure livelihood, raise children, and uphold their status and influence within the community. Family members typically reside close to one another often engaging in intermarriage such as between first cousins although this practice varies across different countries. Regardless of practicality or capability, there exists a strong expectation among family members to provide support to one another with loyalty to the family superseding personal needs. Preserving family honor is of utmost importance and guides the conduct of all family members (Abdul-Haq 
                     2018
                  ).

sidebar.para:
Within the hierarchical structure of the family, older members command significant respect and it is customary for children, especially sons, to assume the responsibility of caring for elderly parents. Consequently, elderly parents are commonly looked after within the family home until their passing, despite the sacrifices involved. In traditional Arab families, the burden of caring for family members primarily falls on older men, with brothers assuming responsibility for unmarried sisters in the absence of the father. In the unfortunate event of a husband’s demise, his family is expected to provide for his widow and children. Family leaders are also expected to leverage their influence to provide support to relatives, although these expectations are shifting as nuclear families increasingly replace extended family structures, leading to challenges in caring for elderly relatives (Abdul-Haq 
                     2018
                  ).

Discrimination-related stressors also significantly impact the work experiences of Arab Americans (Alsaidi et al. 
                     2023
                  ; Kader et al. 
                     2020
                  ). While major incidents of discrimination such as termination and physical assaults are relatively uncommonly reported, instances of intimidation, suspicion, derogatory remarks about religious practices, and patient refusal for treatment by Arab American nurses have been reported (Hashem and Awad 
                     2021
                  ; Saadi et al. 
                     2023
                  ). Arab Americans are acutely aware of prevalent misconceptions held by the broader American society regarding Arabs, including perceptions of inferiority, backwardness, sinister motives, and propensity for violence. Additionally, the misrepresentation of mainstream Islam and the stereotyping of Muslims as extremists and confrontational further exacerbate the challenges faced by Arab Americans in navigating their religious practices within a predominantly secular American society (Hashem and Awad 
                     2021
                  ). Conflicts often arise concerning matters like marriage, divorce, banking, inheritance, and the observance of religious obligations such as Friday prayers and dietary restrictions, particularly among children balancing Islamic requirements with the norms of the American public school system (Fleischer and Sadek 
                     2024
                  ).

sidebar.title:
Nutritional Deficiencies and Food Limitations Nutritional deficiencies and food limitations among individuals of Arab heritage are influenced by various factors, including cultural practices, dietary habits, socioeconomic status, and access to healthcare. While Arab cuisine is known for its rich flavors and ingredients, certain dietary patterns and cultural norms may contribute to specific nutritional concerns. Iron deficiency is a prevalent concern, particularly among women of childbearing age and children due to insufficient dietary intake (Jalambo et al. 
                     2018
                  ). The traditional Arab diet may lack adequate sources of iron, emphasizing the importance of incorporating iron-rich foods such as legumes, fortified cereals, and leafy greens into daily meals to prevent anemia. Limited consumption of dairy products in Arab cultures may contribute to calcium deficiency, impacting bone health. To address this, individuals should be encouraged to consume alternative sources of calcium such as fortified plant-based milk, leafy greens, almonds, and sesame seeds to support optimal bone health. Factors such as limited sun exposure and cultural practices like covering the skin may lead to vitamin D deficiency, especially in regions with minimal sunlight. Dietary sources of vitamin D and supplementation may be necessary to address deficiencies and support bone health and immune function (Masoud et al. 
                     2020
                  ). Individuals following a strict vegetarian or vegan diet in Arab cultures may be at risk of vitamin B12 deficiency due to limited intake of animal products. Incorporating fortified foods or considering supplementation can help prevent deficiencies, particularly among those with limited meat consumption.

sidebar.para:
Gender roles influence fertility practices within Arab families, with women often expected to prioritize motherhood (Sharkia Taubman-Ben-Ari 
                     2024
                  ). Men also play a supportive role in the fertility journey, providing emotional support and participating in family planning decisions. Childbirth is considered a significant life event, and expectant mothers adhere to cultural customs and traditions surrounding childbirth and postpartum care. This includes preferences for specific birthing practices and the involvement of female relatives or midwives during labor. Despite positive attitudes toward pregnancy and childbirth, individuals may encounter stigma associated with infertility or pregnancy loss within Arab communities. Open discussions about reproductive health and support for those experiencing fertility challenges are essential to address stigma and promote well-being.

Modesty is highly valued in Arab culture, particularly concerning matters related to childbirth and the postpartum period (Druker Shitrit et al. 
                     2024
                  ). Women may be expected to maintain modesty by covering their bodies and refraining from interactions with unrelated males during labor and after childbirth. In some Arab communities, women may be subject to dietary restrictions during pregnancy and postpartum. Certain foods or spices believed to be harmful to the mother or baby may be avoided, while others considered beneficial for recovery and lactation may be encouraged.

The degree of religious observance varies among individuals, ranging from nominal adherence to devout practice. However, owing to the intertwined nature of religion and governance in many Arab countries, a certain level of religious engagement is culturally expected. For instance, Islamic principles profoundly influence various facets of life in Jordan, among other Arab countries. Under Islamic law, abortion is considered a criminal act, while foster parenting is encouraged, although adoption is prohibited (Büchler and Schneider Kayasseh 
                     2018
                  ). Infertility treatments sanctioned by Islamic jurists are the only options available. Family matters, including marriage, divorce, guardianship, and inheritance, are adjudicated in Islamic law courts, applying shariah.

sidebar.title:
Folk Practices Folk practices among people of Arab heritage offer a window into the cultural tapestry that shapes daily life and community interactions (El-Shamy 
                     2018
                  ). These practices, deeply rooted in tradition, religion, and social customs reflect a blend of superstitions, healing traditions, and rituals that have been passed down through generations. Despite Islamic teachings discouraging superstition, beliefs in the evil eye, envy, and supernatural entities like jinn persist in Arab folklore (El-Shamy 
                     2018
                  ). Protective measures such as wearing amulets, reciting Quranic verses and invoking the name of Allah are common practices to ward off the evil eye. Concerns about jealousy and envy are particularly associated with the misfortune caused by the evil gaze.

sidebar.para:
Cultural mistrust and discrimination, compounded by historical biases and negative portrayals of Arabs in media and society create additional barriers to healthcare access (Alsaidi et al. 
                     2023
                  ). Arab individuals may fear discrimination or bias from healthcare providers based on ethnicity, religion, or national origin, leading to avoidance of healthcare services or selective disclosure of information. Limited availability of culturally competent care providers proficient in the Arabic language and familiar with Arab customs further delays access to quality care, particularly in regions or healthcare settings where such providers are scarce.

The stigma surrounding mental illness is pervasive within Arab communities, often leading to denial, attributions to “bad nerves” or blame on evil spirits. Lebanese families for example, may deny mental illness altogether fearing community reactions, resulting in underreporting and avoidance of professional help (Pampati et al. 
                     2018
                  ). Consequently, mental distress may manifest as vague complaints like abdominal pain or lassitude, and patients may prefer somatic treatments over counseling with prayer and herbal remedies being more acceptable than psychiatric intervention. Hospitalization may also be resisted due to fears of abandonment further complicating access to mental healthcare. Similarly, attitudes toward disabilities are generally negative with low expectations for education and rehabilitation. Misconceptions about mental retardation persist due to limited exposure and social stigma resulting in the disabled being kept from public view. Family members typically assume caregiving responsibilities, often indulging and protecting the disabled person reflecting acceptance of dependency within Arab culture. These cultural responses underscore the importance of understanding and respecting cultural nuances in healthcare delivery. By acknowledging and addressing these beliefs and attitudes, healthcare providers can foster trust, improve patient-provider communication, and ultimately enhance healthcare outcomes within Arab communities.

In Arab society, medicine is highly esteemed, while nursing is often seen as a less desirable profession due to societal norms that dictate certain behaviors for women. However, efforts are being made in many Arab countries to improve the image of nursing and enhance the working environment for nurses (Wehbe-Alamah et al. 
                     2024
                  ). American nurses are generally viewed more favorably due to their education, expertise, and ability to perform tasks traditionally reserved for physicians such as physical examinations. Younger Arab American immigrants, particularly those from Lebanon, Iraq, and Jordan tend to have more positive perceptions of nursing as a profession compared to the older generation. The hierarchical structure of Arab society is reflected in the roles and status of physicians and nurses. Physicians, typically older males, are seen as authority figures who expect nurses to defer to them in decision-making and information disclosure. Nurses, often younger females, conform to these expectations and may be relegated to roles as medical assistants and housekeepers rather than being recognized as critical thinkers and health educators. However, nursing is gradually gaining recognition as a profession in many Arab countries, with the establishment of professional organizations resembling the American Nurses Association.
